3. Theoretical Foundations

3.1 Causal‑Epistemic Graphs

Let $\mathcal{S}$ be a set of propositions (statements). Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a totally ordered set of timestamps (e.g., $\mathbb{R}$ or $\mathbb{N}$). A knowledge element is defined as:

k_i = (s_i, t_i, \text{causes}_i)

where $s_i \in \mathcal{S}$, $t_i \in \mathcal{T}$, and $\text{causes}_i \subseteq \mathcal{S}$ is a set of causal antecedents. The knowledge base $\mathcal{K}$ is a set of such elements.

The causal‑epistemic graph $\mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{K}, \mathcal{L})$ is a directed graph where $(k_j, k_i) \in \mathcal{L}$ iff $s_j \in \text{causes}_i$. Edges represent causal or evidential influence. In this work we assume the graph is acyclic (i.e., a DAG) to avoid circular dependencies; extensions to cyclic graphs with damping are discussed in future work.

3.2 Epistemic State

Each knowledge element $k_i$ carries an epistemic state:

\epsilon_i = (\mu_i, \sigma_i, \delta_i, \phi_i)

· $\mu_i \in [0,1]$: mean confidence in the truth of $s_i$,
· $\sigma_i \in [0,1]$: uncertainty (standard deviation of belief),
· $\delta_i \in [0,1]$: contradiction score (high when sources conflict),
· $\phi_i \in \{\text{positivist},\text{realist},\text{constructivist},\text{relationist}\}$: onto‑epistemological tag indicating the paradigm under which the statement is considered. (In this framework, $\phi_i$ is a static metadata field; dynamic propagation is left for future work.)

3.3 Epistemic Metric Space

Let $\mathcal{E} = [0,1]^3 \times \Phi$ be the space of epistemic states, where $\Phi$ is the set of tags. For two states $\epsilon_a, \epsilon_b$, we define a metric $d$ on the continuous components (the discrete tag $\phi$ does not affect convergence):

d(\epsilon_a, \epsilon_b) = \sqrt{w_\mu (\mu_a - \mu_b)^2 + w_\sigma (\sigma_a - \sigma_b)^2 + w_\delta (\delta_a - \delta_b)^2}

with $w_\mu, w_\sigma, w_\delta > 0$ normalization constants. The pair $(\mathcal{E}, d)$ is a metric space (up to the discrete tag, which we treat separately).

3.4 Visual Lexicon as an Invertible Encoding

Define a visual lexicon $\Lambda: \mathcal{E} \to \mathcal{C}$, where $\mathcal{C}$ is the space of cinematic parameters (saturation, blur radius, flicker frequency, color grade). The mapping is:

\begin{array}{l|l|l}
\hline
\text{Epistemic Variable} & \text{Parameter} & \text{Mathematical Mapping} & \text{Cinematic Effect} \\
\hline
\mu\ (\text{confidence}) & S\ (\text{saturation}) & S = S_{\max} \cdot \mu & \text{Desaturated = unproven; vivid = fact} \\
\sigma\ (\text{uncertainty}) & \beta\ (\text{blur radius}) & \beta = \beta_0 \cdot \exp(\sigma) & \text{Sharp = known; blurred = speculative} \\
\delta\ (\text{contradiction}) & f\ (\text{flicker frequency}) & f = f_{\text{base}} \cdot \delta & \text{Stable = consensus; flickering = conflict} \\
\phi\ (\text{ontology}) & \gamma\ (\text{color grade}) & \gamma \in \{\text{P}, \text{R}, \text{C}, \text{Rel}\} & \text{Distinct palettes} \\
\hline
\end{array}

Each component mapping is continuous and injective; thus $\Lambda$ is a homeomorphism from $\mathcal{E}$ (ignoring the discrete tag) to its image in $\mathcal{C}$. This ensures that the epistemic state can be uniquely recovered from the visual parameters. We refer to this property as visual invertibility, which prevents epistemic masking.

