4. Formal System Definition

Definition 1 (Cinematic Epistemic System). A CES is a 7‑tuple:

\text{CES} = (\mathcal{S}, \mathcal{T}, \mathcal{K}, \mathcal{G}, E, \mathcal{A}, \mathcal{V})

· $\mathcal{S}$: set of propositions,
· $\mathcal{T}$: linearly ordered timestamps,
· $\mathcal{K}$: knowledge base,
· $\mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{K}, \mathcal{L})$: causal‑epistemic graph (assumed acyclic),
· $E: \mathcal{K} \to \mathcal{E}$: epistemic state assignment,
· $\mathcal{A}: \mathcal{G}^t \to \mathcal{G}^{t+1}$: temporal evolution operator,
· $\mathcal{V}: \mathcal{G} \to \mathcal{C}^*$: the visualization mapping that composes $\Lambda$ with narrative structure, producing a sequence of cinematic frames.

