6. Cinematic Visualization as a Homeomorphism

The visual lexicon $\Lambda$ (Sec. 3.4) is a homeomorphism from the continuous epistemic state space to a subspace of cinematic parameters. The visualization mapping $\mathcal{V}$ composes $\Lambda$ with the narrative structure, generating a video where each segment corresponds to a knowledge element and transitions encode causal links.

Theorem 2 (Epistemic Transparency). If two epistemic states $\epsilon \neq \epsilon'$, their visual representations $\Lambda(\epsilon)$ and $\Lambda(\epsilon')$ are distinct. Consequently, no two distinct epistemic evolutions yield the same cinematic sequence.

Proof. Since $\Lambda$ is injective, distinct states map to distinct visual parameter tuples. The mapping $\mathcal{V}$ applies $\Lambda$ element‑wise, preserving injectivity. ∎

This eliminates “epistemic masking”: the AI cannot visually appear certain when its internal uncertainty is high, or hide contradictions behind a stable image.

